You can add your voice to the tens of thousands of comments posted daily on Express.co.uk and have your say on the big issues facing the country today. Last week, the Metropolitan Police Force concluded its own investigation - dubbed operation Hillman - handing out a grand total of 126 fixed penalty notices. Prime Minister Boris Johnson was fined just once for attending his Downing Street birthday party in June 2020. However, he was not penalised for his attendance at a garden party at Downing Street in May that same year.  The Met’s investigation had prevented one of the Government’s most senior civil servants, Sue Gray, from releasing her own findings in full. She had been able to release an interim version of the report, which criticised "failures of leadership and judgement" in No 10 and the Cabinet Office. Following the conclusion of the Met's investigation, the Government has said it will publish Ms Gray’s report “as soon as possible”. But does it actually matter now whether her report is made public and do you care? HAVE YOUR SAY RIGHT NOW - JOIN THE EXPRESS READER DEBATE IN OUR COMMENTS SECTION. 